SSH provides
   for algorithms that provide authentication, key agreement,
   confidentiality, and data-integrity services.

The hostname is always in US-ASCII (as per RFC1033);
         internationalized hostnames are encoded in US-ASCII as
         specified in RFC 3490.

Output:
            Failure_Indicator;  // Returned if the authentication tag
                                //   is invalid
            octet_string  PT;   // Plain Text, returned if and only if
                                //    the authentication tag is valid

The server could require both password and public key authentication;
   however, this requires the client to expose its password to the
   server (see the section on Password Authentication below.)

o  Transport layer generic messages (1 to 19) (but
      SSH_MSG_SERVICE_REQUEST and SSH_MSG_SERVICE_ACCEPT MUST NOT be
      sent);

Family 1 only (min_LOS 128):
          kex_algorithm name_list         := { ecdh_sha2_nistp256 }
          encryption_algorithm name_list  := { AEAD_AES_128_GCM   }
          mac_algorithm name_list         := { AEAD_AES_128_GCM   }

ファミリー 1 のみ (min_LOS 128):
          kex_algorithm name_list         := { ecdh_sha2_nistp256 }
          encryption_algorithm name_list  := { AEAD_AES_128_GCM   }
          mac_algorithm name_list         := { AEAD_AES_128_GCM   }

ECDSA-384 only (min_LOS 128 or 192):
               server_host_key_algorithms name_list :=
                                { x509v3-ecdsa-sha2-nistp384 }

ECDSA-384 のみ (min_LOS 128 or 192):
               server_host_key_algorithms name_list :=
                                { x509v3-ecdsa-sha2-nistp384 }

